`template/scripts/` is the Layer 1 CI gate plus one-time project bootstrap for repos scaffolded from the CTX template. `ci.sh` is the entry point consumed by CI/agents; everything else here is either a check it invokes or an unrelated setup script (`install-tools.sh`).

The checks share one enumeration convention: file lists come from `git ls-files -z --cached --others --exclude-standard`, never a filesystem walk, so target/ and concurrent build writes never pollute results — `no_allow_check.sh`, `rationale_check.py`, and `workspace_lints_check.sh` all rely on this and must stay consistent if the strategy ever changes. `ci.sh` calls its sibling scripts by path resolved via `SCRIPTS_DIR`, not CWD, and runs every check unconditionally (no short-circuit), aggregating failures via its `RUN`/`PHASE` helpers — a new check script must plug into that pattern rather than `set -e`. Each check script independently accepts an optional root-dir arg (default `.`) and cd's into it, so `ci.sh` can point the whole suite at an arbitrary target repo.

Two checks are explicit MVP placeholders standing in for future dylint rules (documented in docs/DYLINT_RULES.md): `cycle_check.sh` only verifies `cargo-modules` runs, doesn't detect real cycles; `rationale_check.py` enforces size limits via regex/brace-counting heuristics, not a real parser. `no_allow_check.sh` and `workspace_lints_check.sh` are the two policy-enforcement checks with zero tolerance / exact-format matching, respectively — both fragile to unconventional Rust/TOML formatting by design (documented tradeoff, not a bug).

`install-tools.sh` is unrelated to the CI-check family: it's a one-time step run after copying `template/` into a new project, building `ctx-*` binaries from a sibling tooling repo and copying them plus summarizer prompts into the new project so `CLAUDE.md` and hooks resolve correctly.